Why Exploratory Data Analysis of Coffee Shop Sales Trends Project?¶

The project Exploratory Data Analysis of Coffee Shop Sales Trends was undertaken to address the following:

  • Data-Driven Decision Making: Help coffee shop owners understand sales trends and customer preferences to improve business strategies.
  • Customer Insights: Analyze transactional data to uncover patterns in customer behavior, such as peak sales times and preferred products.
  • Performance Optimization: Provide actionable insights for optimizing inventory, staffing, and promotional efforts.
  • Scalable Framework: Build a reusable data analysis framework that can be adapted to other retail datasets.

Impact of this project?¶

  • Enabled better resource allocation by identifying high-performing stores and time slots.
  • Supported marketing strategies by revealing top-selling products and revenue patterns.
  • Established a data-driven approach for making business decisions in competitive retail environments.

Below is the detailed steps of Exploratory Data Analysis of Coffee Shop Sales Trends project:

Conclusion¶

Model Performance¶

  • Decision Tree:
    • Demonstrated consistent performance with an accuracy of 59.33%.
    • Relied on straightforward interpretability, making it a reliable baseline model.
  • Random Forest:
    • Matched the Decision Tree in accuracy (59.33%) but offered better generalization by aggregating multiple trees.
  • Bagging (Decision Tree):
    • Slightly lower accuracy at 59.22%, showing the impact of variability in ensemble methods.
  • Voting Ensemble:
    • Achieved 58.88% accuracy, combining multiple models to enhance decision-making.
    • Its slightly lower performance indicates that individual model contributions need fine-tuning.
  • Logistic Regression:
    • Secured 58.26% accuracy, performing well for linear decision boundaries.
  • Naive Bayes:
    • Had the lowest accuracy at 35.91%, showing its limitations with the given dataset's feature distributions.

Challenges¶

  • Time Complexity:
    • Ensemble methods like Voting and Bagging required more computational resources and longer execution times.
    • Balancing ensemble diversity while maintaining efficiency proved challenging.
  • Implementation Challenges:
    • Fine-tuning hyperparameters across multiple models.
    • Managing and evaluating confusion matrices for each model.

Final Thoughts¶

  • While the Decision Tree and Random Forest showed comparable accuracy, their simplicity and efficiency make them valuable choices for initial analysis.
  • The Voting Ensemble demonstrated the potential of combining multiple models, but its performance suggests room for optimization in model selection and weighting.
  • Future work should explore hyperparameter optimization and advanced ensemble techniques to further improve accuracy and scalability.
